In java, to navigate the execution flow of a program we have to use control flow statements. For example, executing a block of statement based on condition . 
All the control flow statements are categorized  into three types. Those are<br /> <br />
<span class="span" />1) Selection Statements<br />
<span class="span" />2) Iterative Statements <br />
<span class="span" />3) Transfer statements<br /> <br />
<div class="sh">Selection Statements</div><br /> 
If we want to execute a block of statements based on condition, then we have to go for Selection statements. There are two selection statements. Those are<br /><br />
<span class="span" />1) if-else<br />
<span class="span" />2) switch <br /><br />
<div class="sh">Iterative Statements</div><br /> 
If we want to execute a block of statements repeatedly until the condition is false, then we have to go for Iterative Statements. The following are iterative statements provided in java.<br /><br />
<span class="span" />1) while loop<br />
<span class="span" />2) do-while loop<br />
<span class="span" />3) for loop<br />
<span class="span" />4) for-each loop<br /><br />
<div class="sh">Transfer Statements</div><br /> 
If we want to transfer the control from one statement to another statement and if we want break the flow of the program, then we have to go for Transfer Statements. The following are Transfer statements provided in java. Those are.<br /><br />
<span class="span" />1) break<br />
<span class="span" />2) continue<br />
<span class="span" />3) return<br />
<span class="span" />4) finally<br />
<span class="span" />5) try<br />
<span class="span" />6) catch<br /><br />